Executive Summary: SFFD Service Calls Data Platform
Date: April 14, 2026
Subject: Technical Implementation & Performance Analysis of the SFFD Data Platform

1. Project Mission
The goal of this project was to transition the San Francisco Fire Department (SFFD) from a fragmented, manual daily reporting process to an automated, cloud-native analytics platform. The solution successfully automates data ingestion, ensures schema consistency, and provides a high-performance star schema for stakeholder reporting.

2. Technical Achievements (Data Engineering)
Automated Pipeline: Designed an event-driven architecture using Google Cloud Storage (GCS) and BigQuery . New daily extracts are automatically detected and ingested, removing manual intervention (Deliverables 1 & 2).
Robust Transformation Logic: Resolved critical "Column 30" type mismatch errors encountered in the raw source files by implementing a centralized SQL transformation layer. All inconsistent numeric/string fields were standardized to ensure 100% pipeline reliability.
Intelligent Deduplication: Leveraged QUALIFY ROW_NUMBER() logic to process 8,317 raw records down to 3,605 unique, high-quality service call records , ensuring no duplication in final reports (Deliverable 3).
3. Analytics Modeling (The Star Schema)
To support high-speed analysis of call volumes and response times, I implemented a Star Schema (Deliverable 4):

Fact Table ( fact_service_calls ): Stores critical metrics including Response Time (seconds) and Dispatch Delay.
Dimensions ( dim_location , dim_call_type ): Normalizes geography and incident categories to reduce storage costs and increase query speed via integer surrogate keys ( FARM_FINGERPRINT ).
4. Data Quality & Performance Metrics
The platform currently provides the following verified KPIs:

Total Processed Records: 3,605 unique incidents.
Avg. Response Time: Calculated at approximately 10.43 minutes , providing a baseline for service performance monitoring.
Referential Integrity: 100% join success rate between fact and dimension tables.
5. Future Scalability
The implementation is version-controlled and idempotent, making it ready for production deployment via BigQuery Scheduled Queries . The architecture is fully documented (Deliverable 5) and scalable to handle increasing daily call volumes without further engineering overhead.
